    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>122300</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Θευτίμα">Θευτίμα</name> <persName type="attested"><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Ἀρίμμας">Ἀρίμ<supplied reason="omitted">μ</supplied>αντος</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Theutima fille d'Arimmas.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Theutima daughter of Arimmas.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Theutima figlia di Arimmas.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>The rather irregular lettering and the single mu in the father's name give an impression of carelessness. The date is thus rather conjectural.
               It is not impossible that the inscription is contemporary with one or more niches for small busts, hence dating from Roman times.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
